   <abstract >This paper introduces the concept of longstanding anger and seeks to address the thought that maintaining anger indefinitely is corruptive to the character of the agent and destructive to relationships. It denies that anger is inherently harmful and argues that it plays a significant role in the moral landscape as a method of 'valuing the valuable' that cannot be replicated through forgiveness. The paper argues that forgiveness is not morally superior to anger, and our reasons for condemning anger often have to do with discomfort surrounding the presence of discord, rather than anger being unfitting. Anger is explored within its role as a social emotion as conditions are set out for how and when anger can reasonably be maintained indefinitely, showing how it can fittingly not diminish, even upon the death of the wrongdoer. The paper suggests that longstanding anger arises from circumstances when an unrepentant wrongdoer maintains their commitment to the wrong and can be resolved either by the wrongdoer or through recognition of the wrong by the greater social community.</abstract>
